Each plot should be accompanied by a short comment on the relationship between the variable the âSalePriceâ.

Do these relationships match your intuition?

corr = sales %>% select_if(is.numeric) %>% cor(.)

                                 # Mileage  and Sales Price
library(ggplot2)

The correlation between Mileage and Sales Price is highly correlated. This does match my intuition. As I would have thought, the lower the mileage the higher the sales price.

Task 4: Create a correlation plot for the numeric variables. Hint: You will need to exclude one of the variables as it is not numeric.

corr = sales %>% select_if(is.numeric) %>% cor(.)
ggcorrplot(corr, lab = TRUE, digits = 3)

Which variable is most strongly correlated with SalePrice? Which is most weakly correlated?

The variable that is most strongly correlated to SalePrice is Age. (In a positive direction)

The variable that is least correlated to SalePrice is Horsepower. (In a negative direction)

Task 5: Build a linear regression model with the strongest variable (identified in Task 4). Comment on the quality of the model.

ggplot(sales) +
  aes(x = SalePrice, y = Age) +
  geom_point(shape = "circle", size = 1.5, colour = "#112446") +
  theme_minimal()

The quality of this model is not ideal but does display a negative slope. Furthermore, it appears certain cars or model of cars are immune to drop in saleprice. Thus, without the handful of outliers - we do see a liner model (in the negative direction)>

Task 6: Build a linear regression model with the weakest variable (identified in Task 4). Comment on the quality of the model.

ggplot(sales) +
  aes(x = SalePrice, y = Horsepower) +
  geom_point(shape = "circle", size = 1.5, colour = "#112446") +
  theme_minimal()

Looking at this model, I am not sure that there is a clear or definite pattern. There is no linear regression to be had.

Task 7: Build a linear regression model with the Condition variable as the predictor (use only Condition, no other predictor variables). Comment on the quality of the model.

ggplot(sales) +
  aes(x = Condition, y = SalePrice) +
  geom_point(shape = "circle", size = 1.5, colour = "#112446") +
  theme_minimal()

Based on this model, there is a linear trend but not linear regression. There appear to be a floor of low prices that all new cars do not drop down to. The new cars do not appear to have a ceiling. In contrast, the used cars do not appear to have a floor but do have a price ceiling.

There is a little bit of price overlap for the highest priced used cars and the lowest priced new cars.

Overall, the quality of the model is clean and crisp but does not answer our question about linera regression.
